Mid-term Programming with data assignment¶

Premier League Football Analysis¶

Introduction¶

For this assignment, we decided to review the available historical data from British Premier League football. Our main objective is to analyse individual game statistics and their relationship with the game results. We will try to find a good prediction model that can be used for making predictions based on this data. We will also investigate which betting companies odds correlate the best with the final game results.

Description of data set¶

There are several available online sources for relevant statistics that are suitable for this type of project, but we are interested in those sources that contain the most detailed individual statistics for each match of the season. We used data from two online sources, cleaned the data and then combined it into one data set.

The source of data:

https://www.football-data.co.uk/englandm.php

https://footystats.org/download-stats-csv#

Both datasets can be downloaded in CSV format with accompanying notes on the column names. We chose to analyse the data from 2018/2019 season, but the data from other seasons would also fit into our data project.

Data selection¶

We have imported two separate datasets from which, we would like to extract those features that will be relevant in our analysis.

  • There are 380 entries in both datasets that corresponding to the number of matches in the 2018/19 EPL season.
  • The first dataset contains data about each game of that season with statistics such as ball possession, shots on target or card statistics.
  • The second dataset includes additional data such as betting odds of individual bookmakers.

Here we specify the columns we would like to have in each data set and then pass both lists to the DataFrame object.

Creating a unique keys¶

We would like to join both dataframes on each game entry that is unique in each dataframe. For this purpose, we have to create unique keys that can be used for merging both dataframes. One way of doing this is to concatenate strings from multiple columns of each dataframe and create a string that would be unique for each entry. Concatenation of strings from columns such as date, home team name and away team name, will create those unique keys. I decided for the combination of the first 10 letters from the date column with the first three letters of home and away team name. That will create a unique key for each match of the season and could be used for joining both dataframes.

In [11]:

# A function that will return the table with all games of the given team
def get_stats(fav_team):
    newdf = df[(df.home_team_name == fav_team) | (df.away_team_name == fav_team) ]
    newdf= newdf.reset_index(drop=True)
    newdf.index = newdf.index + 1
    return newdf

# To do this, first we have to calculate points for each game, because our dataframe doesn't contain the data about scored points. 
# In our original data set, we only had information about the goals scored by each team in each game, so we create a function to calculate the game points. 
# Three points are awarded for a win, one point for a draw and none for a defeat. 

def calculate_points(x,y):
    if(x > y):
        return 3
    elif(x==y):
        return 1
    else:
        return 0

# We then apply this function on each row of the dataframe. 
df['home_team_points'] = df.apply(lambda row : calculate_points(row['home_team_goal_count'],row['away_team_goal_count']), axis = 1) 
df['away_team_points'] = df.apply(lambda row : calculate_points(row['away_team_goal_count'],row['home_team_goal_count']), axis = 1) 

# We can check the calculation on the sample data.

# For each game, we also add the information of full time result (H=Home Win, D=Draw, A=Away Win). 
def calculate_result(x, y):
    if x==y:
        return 'D'
    elif x>y:
        return 'H'
    else:
        return 'A'
    
df["full_time_result"] = df.apply(lambda row : calculate_result(row['home_team_goal_count'],row['away_team_goal_count']), axis = 1)

Next, we aggregate the game results and create the final table with scored points.

In [18]:
# This function sums the total score of a given team.
def get_final_score(team):
    home_score = df[(df.home_team_name == team)]['home_team_points'].sum()
    away_score = df[(df.away_team_name == team)]['away_team_points'].sum()
    total_score = home_score + away_score
    return total_score

# This function computes the number of games played by a given team.
def count_games_played(team):

    away_played = df[(df.away_team_name == team)]["away_team_name"].count()

We see that the sum of the home win odds, draw odds, and away odds are slightly above 100 per cent. That is the margin that each betting company adds to individual odds and it ranges from 2.35-5.34% on average. The most favourable odds for the clients offers the PSC company, the worst odds offers IW company.

The heatmap shows where the relationship between two variables from the data set is strong or weak. We can see several correlations. A weak correlation is between the number of points and the number of corners or ball possession percentage. The number of corners and the ball possession correlates with shots on target. Shots on target correlate with the number of goals. The strongest correlation is between goals and points. Scored goals have a positive correlation with the points and conceded goals have a negative correlation. Therefore, the ratio between scored goals scored and conceded goals will have a better correlation with the final points. We can calculate this ratio and add it to our data set.

Multinomial Logistic Regression¶

To understand the nature of individual features, we will try to find a regression model that will sufficiently describe the correlations among individual statistics and their relationship on the game result. We tried to fit individual game statistics into linear regression model, but that approach lead to two problems:

  • problem to identify continuous dependant feature that describe the game result

  • distributed y values relative to the regression line

In [69]:
# a linear approximation of the data
x_col = "home_team_shots_on_target"
y_col = "home_team_points"

X = df[x_col].values.reshape(-1,1)
y = df[y_col].values.reshape(-1,1)

model = linear_model.LinearRegression()
model.fit(X,y)
predictions = model.predict(X)
In [71]:
# a scatter plot for the linear regression model
%matplotlib inline
plt.scatter(X,y)
plt.plot(X,predictions, c='red', linewidth=2)

plt.xlabel(x_col)
plt.ylabel(y_col)
Out[71]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'home_team_points')

The graph shows that the relationship of the independent and dependant variable is not linear and we cannot fit a linear regression line into this data. We have ternary categorical data in our dataset for the number of points scored for the game. (3 points for a win, 0 points for a loss, 1 for a draw). When the dependent variable consists of several categories the logistic regression model should be used. We use a multinomial logistic regression model for fitting selected independent variables.

Selecting relevant features¶

We select suitable candidates for independent variables in the regression model. And then we create multiple regression models with various combinations of these variables.

The maximum probability score we could achieve was 0.70 with the lowest AIC (Chaurasia A., Harel. O.,2013) and one of the highest R^2 squared. For a given size of the data set, the p-values of that model can be considered as statistically significant (Anderson, Faye. (2016)). Adding more features doesn't improve the selected criteria. In the next section, we will use this model to make the prediction on the test data.

We calculated the accuracy score. It measures the proportion of correct predictions over total predictions. To objectively measure the performance of this model, we could compare it a with another model trained on the same data. For the unbiased evaluation of the model, the validation dataset could be used. We should also consider the larger dataset for training, for example, data from multiple seasons.

Conclusion¶

When we want to analyze football statistics and their relationship to team performance, we have to take many factors into account.

We were able to identify which statistics from the dataset correlate the most with the team's performance. We tested several combinations to obtain the regression model with the highest accuracy.

We also analyzed the betting odds and their relationship to the game results. We have calculated the average margin that betting companies add to the odds and which betting company offers the best odds.

For futher work¶

We only looked at a small range of relevant game statistics. If we were able to collect more detailed data about offensive, defensive or players statistics, more accurate data analysis could be made.
